@flexiarg writing-coherence/scope-mush
@title Name the Real Reasons Individually, or Not at All
@keywords scope, variety-of-reasons, including-among-others, filler-list, enumeration
@audience paper authors, reviewers
@tone technical
@style pattern
@references [writing-coherence/triad-inflation writing-coherence/hedged-lift]

! conclusion: Constructions like "this matters for a variety of reasons, including..." or "among other things, X, Y, and Z..." typically contain either one real reason padded with filler, or several reasons of unequal weight that would each deserve a sentence.  The mush signals coverage without paying its cost.  Name the reasons individually and defend each, or state a single reason cleanly, or drop the list.
  + context: Scope mush is a form of enumeration that has lost faith in its own items.  The "variety" hedges the quantity; the "including" hedges the selection; the "among other things" hedges both.  AI prose reaches for the mush when the writer has not sorted which reasons are load-bearing.  Readers sense the lack of commitment and discount the whole sentence.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: coverage ↔ specificity.
    Real: a genuinely multi-reason claim deserves enumeration with defences per item.  A single-reason claim deserves one sentence that states the reason cleanly.  Mush optimises for neither.
    Irreducible: a sentence cannot simultaneously claim broad coverage and commit to specific items.  Either the scope is wide and the items are examples, or the scope is narrow and the items are the argument.
    Active: the pull recurs whenever a writer has more than one candidate reason but has not ranked or differentiated them.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Name one and defend it: if one reason is load-bearing, cut the list and state that reason with its defence.  "This matters because X" beats "this matters for a variety of reasons".
    (2) Split into sentences: if several reasons carry distinct weight, give each its own sentence with its own defence.  The enumeration is now an argument, not a gesture.
    (3) Drop the list: if the claim stands alone without a reason catalogue, remove the list entirely.  Readers are not well-served by the variety-claim if the items are not going to work.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: every "variety of reasons" / "among other things" / "including" list in the draft has been rewritten as either a single committed reason or as per-sentence enumerated reasons.  Failing when: lists appear where the items are not individually defended and are not clearly illustrative of a single committed claim.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Variety hedge: "for a variety of reasons, including..." with one real reason and filler.
    - Among-other-things: "among other things, X, Y, and Z" where the "other things" never surface.
    - Uneven weight: a three-item list where item 1 carries the claim and items 2–3 are illustrations promoted to parallel status.
    - Open-ended enumeration: "such as A, B, C, ..." where the trailing "..." exempts the writer from completeness.
